<p>A modular multiplicative inverse of <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">a</span> modulo <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">m</span> can be found by using the extended Euclidean algorithm.
</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/Euclidean_algorithm" title="Euclidean algorithm">Euclidean algorithm</a> determines the greatest common divisor (gcd) of two integers, say <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">a</span> and <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">m</span>. If <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">a</span> has a multiplicative inverse modulo <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">m</span>, this gcd must be 1. The last of several equations produced by the algorithm may be solved for this gcd. Then, using a method called "back substitution", an expression connecting the original parameters and this gcd can be obtained. In other words, integers <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">x</span> and <span class="texhtml mvar" style="font-style:italic;">y</span> can be found to satisfy <a href="/wiki/B%C3%A9zout%27s_identity" title="Bézout&#39;s identity">Bézout's identity</a>,
</p>
<dl><dd><span class="mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"  alttext="{\displaystyle ax+my=\gcd(a,m)=1.}">
